I recently took an assessment and got this as the question. Anyone know how we can solve this ? I used hashmap to group the indexes with the same mean, but it didn't solve all test cases. The order of the result array was messed up.

Here is my solution

public int[][] solution(int[][] a) {
    Map<Double, List<Integer>> map = new HashMap<>();
    for(int i = 0; i < a.length; i++) {
        int[] arr = a[i];
        double sum = 0;
        for(int x : arr) sum += x;
        sum /= arr.length;
        map.putIfAbsent(sum, new ArrayList<>());
        map.get(sum).add(i);
    }
    return map.values().stream().map(l -> l.stream().mapToInt(x->x).toArray()).sorted((x,y)->x[0]-y[0]).toArray(int[][]::new);
}

from collections import defaultdict
def Solution(A):
    map=defaultdict(list)
    for i,lst in enumerate(A):
        sum = 0
        for l in lst:
            sum += l

        mean = sum/len(lst)
        map[mean].append(i)


    ans = [l for l in map.values()]
    ans = sorted(ans,key = lambda x: min(x) )
    return ans

Here's my java solution.

public class Main {
    static int[][] test = new int[][]{{3,3,4,2},
                                   {4,4},
                                   {4,0,3,3},
                                   {2,3},
                                   {3,3,3}};
    
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        for(int[] A : meanGroups(test)) {
            System.out.println(Arrays.toString(A));
        }

    }
    
    private static int[][] meanGroups(int[][] nums) {
        
        Map<Integer, List<Integer>> map = new HashMap<>();
        
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            
            int mean = getMean(nums[i]);
            if(!map.containsKey(mean)) map.put(mean, new ArrayList<>());
            map.get(mean).add(i);
            
        }
        
        int[][] ret = new int[map.size()][];
        
        int j = 0;
        
        for(int key: map.keySet()) 
            ret[i++] = map.get(key).stream().mapToInt(j -> j).toArray();
           
        
        Arrays.sort(ret, (a,b) -> a[0] - b[0]);
        return ret;
    }
    
    private static int getMean(int[] A) {
        int sum = 0;
        for(int a: A) {
            sum += a;
        }
        
        return sum/A.length;
    }
}

I think if you iterate over the groups in order and store it in a LinkedHashMap, your map entries/groups will be sorted in the order of array groups.i.e. Group containing smaller array indices would come first.

here is my solution

class Solution {
	private:
		float findMean(vector<int>& nums) {
			float ans = 0;
			for (auto& num : nums) {
				ans += num;
			}
			return ans / nums.size();
		}
		
	public:
		vector<vector<int>> getGroups(vector<vector<int>>& numsVec) {
			unordered_map<float, vector<int>> meanToElementMap;
			for (int i=0; i < numsVec.size(); i++) {
				float mean = findMean(numsVec[i]);
				if (meanToElementMap.count(mean) != 0) {
					meanToElementMap[mean].emplace_back(i);
				} else {
					vector<int> elements;
					elements.emplace_back(i);
					meanToElementMap[mean] = std::move(elements);
				}
			}
			vector<vector<int>> ans;
			for (auto& meanToElement : meanToElementMap) {
				ans.emplace_back(meanToElement.second);
			}
            auto comparator = [](vector<int>& a, vector<int>& b){
                return     *min_element(a.begin(),a.end()) 
                        <= *min_element(b.begin(),b.end());
            };
            sort(ans.begin(), ans.end(), comparator);
			return ans;
		}
};

int main() {
    std::cout << "Hello World!\n";
    Solution solution;
    vector<vector<int>> input = {{3,3,4,2},{4,4},{4,0,3,3}, {2,3},{3,3,3}};
    vector<vector<int>> ans = solution.getGroups(input);
    
    for (auto& nums : ans) {
        for (auto& num : nums) {
            cout << num << " ";
        }
        cout << endl;
    }
}
